         <abstract>
            <p>Let $\{Q_n\}^\infty_{n = 1}$ denote a sequence of quadrature formulas, $Q_n(f) \equiv \sum^{k_n}_{j = 1} w^{(n)}_j f(x^{(n)}_j)$, such that $Q_n(f) \rightarrow \int^1_0 f(x) dx$ for all $f \in C\lbrack 0, 1 \rbrack$. Let $0 &lt; \epsilon &lt; \frac{1}{4}$ and a sequence $\{a_n\}^\infty_{n = 1}$ be given, where $a_1 \geqq a_2 \geqq a_3 \geqq \cdots$, and where $a_n \rightarrow 0$ as $n \rightarrow \infty$. Then there exists a function $f \in C\lbrack 0, 1 \rbrack$ and a sequence $\{n_k\}^\infty_{k = 1}$ such that $|f(x)| \leqq 2a_1/|(1 - 4\epsilon)|$, and such that $\int^1_0 f(x) dx - Q_{n_k}(f) = a_k, k = 1, 2, 3, \cdots$.</p>
          </abstract>
